<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="127" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="127">
Comments: The 
<typeStatus box="[309,459,797,836]" pageId="4" pageNumber="127">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Walker" authorityName="Walker" box="[518,855,797,834]" class="Insecta" family="Apioceridae" genus="Apiocera" genus.bestMatchDistance="491" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alastor">
A. 
<emphasis box="[569,693,797,828]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="127">alastor</emphasis>
(Walker)
</taxonomicName>
is currently a ‘mosaic’, consisting of parts from different specimens. Its body belongs to the original specimen seen by Walker, but the head is from a different (probably Australian) species. The holotype’s head was clearly present originally, as Walker described its features, including the black palpi with black bristles. The replacement head has light brown-yellow palpi with yellow-white hairs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="127">This species is only represented in collections by a handful of specimens, all from the southwestern Cape (Fig. 10).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
